We need to determine if this change can produce a different result under the fixed-shape contract: batch_size=128, element_count=4096, block dims 256 for both kernels. The final_mean_kernel is launched with 1 block of 256 threads. The loop iterates over batch_means indices from tid to batch_size (128) with stride 255. Since batch_size=128, only threads with tid < 128 will have at least one iteration (i=tid, then i+=255 >= 128). For tid=0, i=0, then 255 (>=128) so only one iteration. For tid=1, i=1, then 256 (>=128) stop. So each thread from 0 to 127 accesses exactly one element (its own index). Threads 128 to 255 have i >= 128 initially, so they never enter the loop (since condition i < batch_size is false). So the accumulation is exactly the same as with stride 256: each thread 0-127 reads batch_means[tid] once. The shared memory reduction then sums these 128 values. The result is the sum of all batch_means, then divided by batch_size. So the mutation does not change the behavior for batch_size=128. However, the contract says shape is fixed: batch_size=128, element_count=4096. So under this fixed configuration, the mutant is indistinguishable from the original. The original stride 256 also would have each thread 0-127 access one element (i=tid, then i+=256 >=128). So both produce the same sum. The mutation only changes stride, but since the condition i < batch_size prevents any thread from going beyond one iteration (because 255 > 128), the access pattern is identical. The only difference would be if batch_size were such that stride 255 causes multiple accesses or skipping. But batch_size is fixed at 128. So the mutant is unkillable under the fixed-shape contract. The previous tests with batch_size stress (auxiliary track) tested batch_sizes 1,2,4,8,16,32,64 and all survived. Those are all less than 256, but still, the stride 255 and 256 would behave identically for these sizes as well? Let's check: For batch_size=64, threads 0-63 access one element each with stride 255 (since 0+255=255 >=64, only one iteration). With stride 256, same. So all those batch sizes also survive. The only way to distinguish is to have batch_size > 255, so that stride 255 causes some threads to have multiple iterations, while stride 256 would have exactly one per thread. But batch_size is fixed at 128, less than 256, so the mutation is effectively a no-op. Therefore, the mutant is unkillable under the given contract. The reasoning category: predicate_unreachable? Actually the mutation changes a loop stride, but the loop condition ensures it doesn't affect behavior because the stride is larger than the iteration range. More precisely, the mutation is value_insensitive (the stride change does not affect the computed sum because the loop only iterates once per thread in both cases). But could there be an effect on floating-point summation? No, because the same elements are summed in the same order by each thread. For example, thread 0 sums element 0, thread 1 sums element 1, etc. Exactly the same. So the mutation is semantically neutral. So killable: false. We need to output JSON accordingly. The mutation is not reachable as a difference. So reason_category: "value_insensitive" or "predicate_unreachable"? Actually the mutation is reachable (the code executes), but the change in stride does not produce any difference because the loop body only executes at most once for any thread due to batch_size < stride. So it's value_insensitive. Proof sketch: batch_size=128, stride=255. For any thread tid, the loop condition i < batch_size is true only when i = tid (since tid < 128). Then i += 255 becomes >= batch_size, so no further iterations. Same as stride=256. Therefore identical behavior. Survival reason: The mutation changes the stride from 256 to 255 in the final reduction kernel's accumulation loop. However, given the fixed batch size of 128, which is less than both strides, each thread accesses exactly one element (its own index) and then the loop exits. 